In 2012, Chair of the [[Welsh Affairs Select Committee]] [[David T. C. Davies]] stated that the British government had not been responsible for suppressing the Welsh language in the 19th century, saying that the practice took place before government involvement in the education system began with the [[Elementary Education Act 1870|Education Act 1870]], and that "the teachers who imposed the Welsh Not were Welsh and its imposition would have been done with the agreement of parents".<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|last=Shipton|first=Martin|date=17 November 2012|title=Welsh Not 'a myth to stir up prejudice against the British Government'|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/welsh-not-a-myth-stir-2017604|access-date=16 October 2021|website=WalesOnline|language=en}}</ref>


The first academic study of the Welsh Not was completed by Martin Johnes in 2024.{{Sfn|Johnes|2024|pp=22, 27–28}} He states that some government officials did want Welsh to cease to exist but the government never introduced policies to that end and believed that some use of Welsh was necessary in schools to effectively teach English.{{Sfn|Johnes|2024|p=13}} He comments that the state had limited influence over the school system in the 19th century and it did not prohibit the use of Welsh in schools.{{Sfn|Johnes|2024|pp=197–198}} Johnes argued that there is little evidence to suggest that the Welsh Not caused the decline of Welsh. A large majority of children were not attending day school when it was most common and schools that attempted to completely exclude Welsh tended to be ineffective at teaching English.{{Sfn|Johnes|2024|pp=239–240}} He argued that;{{Sfn|Johnes|2024|p=360}}<blockquote>[The Welsh Not] was not a primary cause of linguistic change but the result of pedagogical misunderstandings and people’s desire for English.
